\begin_layout Standard
Start in the canonical formalism.
 Here, fields are Heisenberg picture operators (actually operator valued
 distributions) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 with accompanying canonical momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 which obey canonical 
\emph on
equal time
\emph default
 commutation relationships
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=\left[\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=0,\\
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{y},t\right)\right]=i\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{x}-\boldsymbol{y}\right).
\end{gather}

\end_inset

Commutators at unequal times must be found by evolving the field with its
 equations of motion.
 For a free field this can be done exactly.
 The free field Hamiltonian is quadratic in fields and momenta, exactly
 analogous to the QM harmonic oscillator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{0}=\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\frac{1}{2}\hat{\pi}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\nabla\hat{\phi}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\hat{\phi}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a parameter with dimensions of inverse length (which is equal to mass
 
\begin_inset Formula $m\hbar/c$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=c=1$
\end_inset

).
 The Hamiltonian equations of motion are then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{t}\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right) & =-i\left[\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{H}_{0}\left(t\right)\right]=\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\\
\partial_{t}\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right) & =-i\left[\hat{\pi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right),\hat{H}_{0}\left(t\right)\right]=\nabla^{2}\hat{\phi}-m^{2}\hat{\phi},
\end{align}

\end_inset

which can be rearranged to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\partial_{t}^{2}-\nabla^{2}+m^{2}\right)\hat{\phi}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the 
\emph on
Klein-Gordon
\emph default
 equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

, and an analogous equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 As a linear equation, this can be solved by Fourier decomposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t\right)=\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\mathrm{e}^{i\left(\boldsymbol{k}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}t\right)}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-i\left(\boldsymbol{k}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}t\right)}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\sqrt{\boldsymbol{k}^{2}+m^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and taking into account that, as a real scalar field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}^{\dagger}=\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the normalisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\sqrt{\frac{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}f_{\boldsymbol{k}}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and applying the equal time commutation relations leads then to the commutation
 relations
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Check 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

s etc.
 here:
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}\right]=\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\right]=0,\\
\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\right]=f_{\boldsymbol{k}}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{q}\right),
\end{gather}

\end_inset

for the mode operators.
 It is conventional to take 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\boldsymbol{k}}=1$
\end_inset

, which is used in all the following.
 With this choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\right)$
\end_inset

 are annihilation(creation) operators for particles with bosonic statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the mode expansion the free Hamiltonian becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{0}=\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(2\pi\right)^{3}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the formal commutator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 was used.
 Using the Fourier representation of the delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=\left(2\pi\right)^{-3}\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\mathrm{e}^{i\boldsymbol{x}\cdot\boldsymbol{0}}=\left(2\pi\right)^{-3}\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of space, the second term can be written
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\left(2\pi\right)^{3}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\frac{1}{2}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=\left(\frac{1}{2}\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\right)\mathrm{V},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which assigns an energy density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 to the vacuum.
 Subtracting this (divergent) vacuum energy density gives the normal ordered
 Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
:\hat{H}_{0}:=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}\ \omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}a_{\boldsymbol{k}}=\int\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}\ \omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}\hat{N}_{\boldsymbol{k}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 is the number operator for the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $:\hat{H}_{0}:$
\end_inset

 describes non-interacting (because the energy is additive) particle-like
 bosonic excitations of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the unequal time commutator can be found:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right] & =\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\int_{\boldsymbol{q}}N_{\boldsymbol{q}}\left[\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}\mathrm{e}^{ikx}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-ikx},\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}\mathrm{e}^{iqy}+\hat{a}_{\boldsymbol{q}}^{\dagger}\mathrm{e}^{-iqy}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}N_{\boldsymbol{k}}\int_{\boldsymbol{q}}N_{\boldsymbol{q}}\delta^{\left(3\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{k}-\boldsymbol{q}\right)\left(\mathrm{e}^{i\left(kx-qy\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-i\left(kx-qy\right)}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\int\frac{\mathrm{d}^{3}\boldsymbol{k}}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}}\left(\mathrm{e}^{ik\left(x-y\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-ik\left(x-y\right)}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the time component of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 in the exponentials.
 Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are spacelike separated, there is a frame in which the time component of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}-y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 vanishes.
 In this case one can see that the commutator vanishes by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}\to-\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

 in the second term.
 To show that this holds in all frames one needs to show that the integration
 measure is in fact Lorentz invariant, as the exponentials are manifestly
 invariant.
 Consider the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}}=\int\mathrm{d}k_{0}\delta\left(k_{0}^{2}-\omega_{\boldsymbol{k}}^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right)=\int\mathrm{d}k_{0}\delta\left(k^{2}-m^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x\right),\hat{\phi}\left(y\right)\right] & =\int_{k}\left(2\pi\right)^{4}\delta\left(k^{2}-m^{2}\right)\Theta\left(k_{0}\right)\left(\mathrm{e}^{ik\left(x-y\right)}-\mathrm{e}^{-ik\left(x-y\right)}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is manifestly invariant under the isochronous (i.e.
 not reversing time) Lorentz transformations.
 Thus fields commute at spacelike separation.
 This is the 
\emph on
microcausality
\emph default
 condition and effectively implements the speed of light limit for information
 transmission.
 Microcausality holds for the free field theory, but also for the interacting
 theories of physical interest
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The main exception being electromagnetism in the Coulomb gauge, which explicitly
 breaks Lorentz invariance.
 In this cause the (gauge variant) commutators do not vanish at spacelike
 separations but causality problems are avoided because only gauge invariant
 quantities are physically observable.
 All gauge invariant quantities can be equally well computed in a Lorentz
 covariant gauge in which microcausality is manifest at every step.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
REF
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and is automatic if the theory is constructed from a Lorentz invariant
 action which is the integral of a local density which is a finite order
 polynomial of fields and their derivatives 
