status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
REF
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since spacelike separated fields commute, the set of fields on a spacelike
 hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 forms a complete commuting set of operators and a complete set of eigenvectors
 can be found.
 Arbitrary states can be expanded in this basis as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Ket{\Psi}=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\left(x\in\Sigma\right)\right]\Psi\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 is the wavefunctional and the Heisenberg states 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 are eigenvectors of the field operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\phi\left(x\right);\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 is generally 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 an eigenvector of a field operator 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 on the hypersurface.
 The time variable hidden in the notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is merely part of the label for the state and implies nothing about its
 time evolution (indeed Heisenberg states do not evolve).
 The notation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $;\Sigma$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used to remind us of this fact.
 Now consider a transition amplitude between an initial and final state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{i}\to\Psi_{f}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Braket{\Psi_{f}|\Psi_{i}} & = & \int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi_{i}\left(x\in\Sigma_{i}\right),\phi_{f}\left(x\in\Sigma_{f}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 &  & \times\Psi_{f}^{\star}\left[\phi_{f}\left(x\right)\right]\Braket{\phi_{f}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{f}|\phi_{i}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{i}}\Psi_{i}\left[\phi_{i}\left(x\right)\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the initial and final hypersurfaces are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 respectively and by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 is later than 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 any future directed timelike curve passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 at proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 at a proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}>\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 From this equation it is clear that the time evolution problem reduces
 to finding
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Braket{\phi_{f}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{f}|\phi_{i}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{i}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the transition amplitude between field eigenstates on two spacelike hypersurface
s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This goal is accomplished by the 
\emph on
Feynman path integral
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
functional integral
\emph default
.
 The idea is to do the time evolution a little bit at a time.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 is later than 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 it is possible to break the finite time evolution into a succession of
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 steps 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}\to\Sigma_{1}\to\Sigma_{2}\to\cdots\to\Sigma_{N-1}\to\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

 and take the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit such that each step represents an infinitesimal time evolution.
 Formally this is done by repeatedly inserting resolutions of the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbb{I}}=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\left(x\in\Sigma\right)\right]\Ket{\phi;\Sigma}\Bra{\phi;\Sigma},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

obtaining
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Braket{\phi_{f}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{f}|\phi_{i}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{i}} & = & \int\prod_{k=1}^{N-1}\mathcal{D}\left[\phi_{k}\left(x\in\Sigma_{k}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 &  & \times\Braket{\phi_{f}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{f}|\phi_{N-1}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{N-1}}\nonumber \\
 &  & \times\cdots\times\Braket{\phi_{k+1}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{k+1}|\phi_{k}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{k}}\nonumber \\
 &  & \times\cdots\times\Braket{\phi_{1}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{1}|\phi_{i}\left(x\right);\Sigma_{i}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

To simplify this further one can assume that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

s are all flat and parallel (the general case can be recovered from the
 final result).
 This means that there is an inertial coordinate system where the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}$
\end_inset

 is constant on each 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 One can further assume, without loss of generality, that the hypersurfaces
 are equally spaced.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}=t_{i}+\epsilon k$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=\left(t_{f}-t_{i}\right)/N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now all one needs is the infinitesimal step
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Braket{\phi_{k+1}\left(x\right);t_{k}+\epsilon|\phi_{k}\left(x\right);t_{k}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Intuitively, there is not much time for the fields to evolve, so this should
 be close to the delta functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx\delta\left[\phi_{k+1}-\phi_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 To find the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

 correction it is easiest to convert the states into the Schr
