\begin_layout Standard
In order to make practical use of the functional integral it is necessary
 to have some way of characterising the initial and final states, handling
 the overall normalisation and evaluating the integral itself.
 Each of these typically require regularisation to handle divergences and
 renormalisation to express the input parameters in terms of physical observable
s.
 The way all of these are implemented depends on the physical application
 being considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the setting of most particle physics is vacuum field theory.
 One is usually interested in the scattering of a small number of particles
 which only interact in a small spacetime region.
 Long before and after the interaction the particles are effectively free,
 so the initial and final states can be approximated by free particle states
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim a_{\boldsymbol{k}_{1}}^{\dagger}a_{\boldsymbol{k}_{2}}^{\dagger}\cdots a_{\boldsymbol{k}_{n}}^{\dagger}\Ket{\text{vac}}$
\end_inset

 and the appropriate observable is the S-matrix element.
 The 
\emph on
Lehmann-Symanzik-Zimmermann
\emph default
 (LSZ) reduction formulae connect the S-matrix elements for the asymptotic
 free particle states to the vacuum-to-vacuum transition matrix elements
 of a time ordered product of interacting fields (a 
\emph on
correlation
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
Green function
\emph default
).
 The essential idea of the LSZ formulae is that, while the free field operators
 create and destroy single particles, interacting fields have some amplitude
 to create and destroy multi-particle states.
 Nevertheless, multi-particle wave packets spread differently than single
 particle wave packets, so that the single particle contributions can be
 isolated and related to the asymptotic free particle states.
 The Green functions can be evaluated by using, essentially, the formulae
 of the previous section.
 However it is necessary to characterise the initial and final physical
 vacuum state and handle the overall normalisation.
 The 
\emph on
Gell-Mann
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Low
\emph default
 theorem accomplishes both.
 The idea is that, instead of trying to find the wavefunctional of the vacuum
 state, one can use 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 physically reasonable initial and final states
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The only condition is that they have non-zero overlap with the vacuum state.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:phi-eigenstate-transition-amplitude-pi"

\end_inset

 and deform the time contour in a slight negative imaginary direction, so
 that one eventually takes the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}\to-\infty\left(1-i\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f}\to+\infty\left(1-i\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The imaginary time component introduces a dissipative part to the time
 evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\exp\left(-\epsilon t\hat{H}\right)$
\end_inset

 which damps all states except for the lowest energy, i.e.
 vacuum, state.
 So finally in the limit only the vacuum-to-vacuum matrix element survives
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This assumes that the vacuum state is non-degenerate and separated by a
 finite spectral gap from any excited states.
 In particular, this implies that this formalism for vacuum field theory
 is strictly speaking invalid for massless particles.
 Yet, massless particles can be handled in this formalism provided one takes
 care of infrared (i.e.
 low energy) divergences and computes inclusive cross sections, i.e.
 including processes with the emission of extra soft particles in the final
 state which are invisible in realistic detectors.
 A detailed treatment of these issues is beyond the scope of this thesis,
 but can be found in e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Peskin1995"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The normalisation factor is taken care of by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Braket{\text{vac}|\text{vac}}=1$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 an undisturbed vacuum remains vacuum.
 Thus one can simply divide by this factor, giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Braket{\text{vac}|\mathrm{T}\left[\hat{\phi}\left(x_{1}\right)\cdots\hat{\phi}\left(x_{n}\right)\right]|\text{vac}}=\frac{\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\phi\left(x_{1}\right)\cdots\phi\left(x_{n}\right)\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{x}\mathcal{L}\left(\phi\right)\right)}{\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{x}\mathcal{L}\left(\phi\right)\right)},\label{eq:vacuum-to-vacuum-transition-matrix-element}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the functional integrals are over all spacetime and any ambiguity
 in the normalisation of the measure simply cancels between the numerator
 and denominator of the ratio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In thermal equilibrium one is not interested in the S-matrix as there are
 no asymptotic states.
 Rather one is interested in the partition function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\mathrm{Tr}\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\hat{H}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/T$
\end_inset

 is the inverse temperature.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 all thermodynamic functions can be derived.
 The trick to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 in the 
\emph on
Matsubara
\emph default
 
\emph on
formalism
\emph default
 is to note that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-\beta\hat{H}\right)$
\end_inset

 is formally an imaginary time evolution operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-i\hat{H}t/\hbar\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=-i\hbar\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore one 
\emph on
Wick rotates
\emph default
 to imaginary time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=x^{0}=-i\hbar x^{4}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{4}$
\end_inset

 goes from zero to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the trace operation implies periodic boundary conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \mathrm{Tr}\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\hat{H}}\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{a}\Braket{a|\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\hat{H}}|a}\nonumber \\
 & = & \int\mathcal{D}\left[a\right]\int_{\phi\left(t=0\right)=a}^{\phi\left(t=-i\hbar\beta\right)=a}\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{0}^{-i\hbar\beta}\mathrm{d}t\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\mathcal{L}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \int_{\phi\left(t=0\right)=\phi\left(t=-i\hbar\beta\right)}\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{0}^{-i\hbar\beta}\mathrm{d}t\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\mathcal{L}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \int_{\phi\left(x^{4}=0\right)=\phi\left(x^{4}=\beta\right)}\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left(\int_{0}^{\beta}\mathrm{d}x^{4}\int_{\boldsymbol{x}}\mathcal{L}_{E}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the 
\emph on
Euclidean
\emph default
 Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{E}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by making the replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to-i\hbar x^{4}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The overall normalisation is either irrelevant (because the observable
 is a ratio, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{O}\right\rangle =\mathrm{Tr}\left(\hat{O}\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\hat{H}}\right)/Z$
\end_inset

) or can be fixed from the requirement that thermodynamic functions (e.g.
 pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\partial_{V}\left(T\ln Z\right)$
\end_inset

) vanish at zero temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These aspects can be illustrated by the case of a free field theory, for
 which
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{x_{E}}\mathcal{L}_{E}=-\frac{1}{2}\int_{x_{E}}\left(\left(\partial_{x^{4}}\phi\right)^{2}+\left(\nabla\phi\right)^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right)=-\frac{1}{2}\int_{x_{E}}\phi D\phi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=-\partial_{x^{4}}^{2}-\nabla^{2}+m^{2}=-\nabla_{E}^{2}+m^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{E}$
\end_inset

 is the obvious Euclidean space gradient operator.
 The following discussion closely follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kapusta_finite-temperature_2006"

\end_inset

.
 The functional integral is easiest to evaluate in the eigenbasis of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 periodic functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp i\left(\boldsymbol{p}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}+\omega_{n}x^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 where the Matsubara frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n}=2\pi n/\beta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 implement the periodic boundary condition.
 It is also convenient to quantise in a spatial box of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}=L^{3}$
\end_inset

 with periodic boundary conditions, making 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}$
\end_inset

 discrete with lattice spacing 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi/L$
\end_inset

.
 The convenient basis functions are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{n\boldsymbol{p}}=\sqrt{\frac{\beta}{\mathrm{V}}}\mathrm{e}^{i\left(\boldsymbol{p}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}+\omega_{n}x^{4}\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which are normalised so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Braket{\phi_{m\boldsymbol{q}}|\phi_{n\boldsymbol{p}}}=\beta^{2}\delta_{mn}\delta_{\boldsymbol{p}\boldsymbol{q}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, on functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Braket{f|g}\equiv\int_{x_{E}}f^{\star}g$
\end_inset

.
 With these normalisations the Fourier amplitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

 in
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi=\sum_{n\boldsymbol{p}}A_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\phi_{n\boldsymbol{p}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

are dimensionless.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{x_{E}}\mathcal{L}_{E}=-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\left|A_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\right|^{2}\beta^{2}\left(\omega_{n}^{2}+\boldsymbol{p}^{2}+m^{2}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functional integrand does not depend on the phases of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

, so these contribute to the normalisation.
 The integrals over the magnitudes are Gaussian, giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=N'\prod_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\left[\beta^{2}\left(\omega_{n}^{2}+\boldsymbol{p}^{2}+m^{2}\right)\right]^{-1/2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where all the normalisation factors are absorbed in 
\begin_inset Formula $N'$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\ln Z & = & \ln N'-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\ln\left[\beta^{2}\left(\omega_{n}^{2}+\boldsymbol{p}^{2}+m^{2}\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \ln N'-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n\boldsymbol{p}}\left\{ \ln\left[\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}+1\right]+\int_{1}^{\beta^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{p}^{2}+m^{2}\right)}\frac{\mathrm{d}\theta^{2}}{\theta^{2}+\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & = & \ln N'-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left\{ \sum_{n}\ln\left[\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}+1\right]+\int_{1}^{\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}\mathrm{d}\theta\left(1+\frac{2}{\mathrm{e}^{\theta}-1}\right)\right\} \nonumber \\
 & = & \ln N'-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left\{ \sum_{n}\ln\left[\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}+1\right]+\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}-1+\int_{1}^{\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}\mathrm{d}\theta\frac{2}{\mathrm{e}^{\theta}-1}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & = & \ln N'-\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\sum_{n}\ln\left[\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}+1\right]+\frac{1}{2}+\ln\frac{1}{\mathrm{e}-1}\right\} \nonumber \\
 &  & -\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left[\frac{1}{2}\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}+\ln\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}\right)\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}1/\left(n^{2}+\left(\theta/2\pi\right)^{2}\right)=\left(2\pi^{2}/\theta\right)\left(1+2/\left(\mathrm{e}^{\theta}-1\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 was used to get the third line.
 The rest of the steps are straightforward evaluations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demanding that the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\partial\left(T\ln Z\right)/\partial T\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $T\to0$
\end_inset

 fixes the normalisation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N'=\exp\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left\{ \frac{1}{2}\sum_{n}\ln\left[\left(2\pi n\right)^{2}+1\right]+\frac{1}{2}+\ln\frac{1}{\mathrm{e}-1}\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and finally (on taking the infinite volume limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\boldsymbol{p}}\to\mathrm{V}\int_{\boldsymbol{p}}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln Z=-\mathrm{V}\int_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left[\frac{1}{2}\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}+\ln\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}\right)\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The energy density is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\frac{E}{\mathrm{V}}=-\frac{\partial_{\beta}\ln Z}{\mathrm{V}}=\int_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left(\frac{1}{2}\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}+\frac{\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}{\mathrm{e}^{\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}-1}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the familiar Bose-Einstein contribution plus a vacuum energy contributi
on which can be subtracted.
 Similarly, the pressure is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P=T\partial_{\mathrm{V}}\ln Z=-\int_{\boldsymbol{p}}\left[\frac{1}{2}\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}+T\ln\left(1-\mathrm{e}^{-\beta\omega_{\boldsymbol{p}}}\right)\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that there is a vacuum contribution to the pressure as well.
 The fact that this contribution is equal to the negative of the vacuum
 energy is in fact a consequence of Lorentz invariance
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The energy-momentum tensor of a Lorentz invariant state must be proportional
 to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}\propto\eta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 since there are no other spacetime tensors available to construct it from.
 Thus the pressure (i.e.
 the diagonal space-space components) is equal and opposite to the energy
 density (the time-time component).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and this provides a nice check of the formalism.
\end_layout

